<h3>Question 3</h3>
<div><p><p>Write a newspaper article in about 250 words making a comparison and contrast between different forms of computer set like desktop, laptop, palmtop or others based on their functions mode, facilities ease and access, difficulty and complexity (including technical description).</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>&nbsp;</p>
<h1 style="text-align: center;">The Kathmandu Daily</h1>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p style="text-align: right;">19th July 2023</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Title: Exploring Computer Setups: A Comparison of Desktops, Laptops, Palmtops, and More </strong></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>In today&#8217;s fast-paced world, computers have become an integral part of our daily lives, catering to diverse needs with varying setups. Each computer type offers unique features and capabilities to suit different user preferences. Let&#8217;s delve into a comparison of the most popular setups, namely desktops, laptops, palmtops, and others, based on their functions, facilities, ease of access, and complexity. <strong>Desktop Computers: </strong></p>
<p>Desktops are powerful and versatile setups, designed for stationary use. They excel in processing-intensive tasks such as video editing and gaming due to their larger form factor and room for high-end hardware. With multiple ports and slots, connecting peripherals is effortless. However, their limited portability restricts usage to a fixed location.</p>
<p><strong>Laptops: </strong></p>
<p>Laptops strike a balance between performance and mobility. They are suitable for both work and leisure, allowing users to be productive on the go. While not as powerful as desktops, they offer convenience with built-in keyboards and touchpads. However, their smaller screens and reduced cooling capacity may affect performance during prolonged usage.</p>
<p><strong>Palmtops/Smartphones: </strong></p>
<p>Palmtops, or smartphones, are pocket-sized computers ideal for communication and light tasks. They offer exceptional portability and instant access to information, making them a go-to choice for mobile professionals and casual users. Nevertheless, their limited processing power and screen size may hinder complex tasks.</p>
<p><strong>Others (Tablets/2-in-1s): </strong></p>
<p>Tablets and 2-in-1 devices provide a mix of laptop and palmtop features. With touchscreens and detachable keyboards, they offer flexibility for various applications. They excel in content consumption and light productivity tasks. However, their processing capabilities might be limited compared to dedicated laptops or desktops.</p>
<p><strong>Ease of Access and Complexity: </strong></p>
<p>Desktops are typically easy to set up and upgrade, given their modular design. In contrast, laptops and palmtops offer a plug-and-play experience with minimal configuration required. However, hardware upgrades in laptops and palmtops may pose challenges due to compact designs.</p>
<p>In conclusion, choosing the right computer setup depends on individual needs and preferences. For power users seeking performance, desktops are the go-to option, while those seeking mobility and versatility may opt for laptops or 2-in-1s. Palmtops and smartphones cater to users on the move, fulfilling essential tasks efficiently. Understanding the distinct features and functionalities of each setup empowers users to make informed decisions, ensuring seamless computing experiences tailored to their requirements.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 4</h3>
<div><p><p>Write instructions about loading photos in a file of the computer and how to use those photos in different facts of a seminar report of your college. Also give instruction about using photoshop program in the computer.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p style="text-align: center;"><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Instructions for Loading Photos and Using Them in a Seminar Report</strong></span></p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li><strong> Loading Photos on Your Computer: </strong></li>
</ol>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Create a folder on your computer to keep all the seminar-related photos in one place. Organize them by categories or events for easy access.</li>
<li>Connect your camera or smartphone to the computer using a USB cable or use a memory card reader to transfer photos. Copy and paste the photos into the designated folder.</li>
</ul>
<ol start="2">
<li><strong> Inserting Photos in the Seminar Report: </strong></li>
</ol>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Launch your preferred word processing software (e.g., Microsoft Word, Google Docs) and open your seminar report.</li>
<li>Position the cursor where you want to insert a photo in the document. Ensure there&#8217;s enough space for the photo to fit without disrupting the text flow.</li>
<li>Click on &#8220;Insert&#8221; in the top menu and select &#8220;Picture&#8221; or &#8220;Image&#8221; from the dropdown menu. Browse to the location of the photo on your computer and click &#8220;Insert.&#8221;</li>
</ul>
<ol start="3">
<li><strong> Captioning Photos: </strong></li>
</ol>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>After inserting the photo, add a caption below it to provide context or a brief description of the image&#8217;s relevance to the seminar report.</li>
<li>Format the caption with a slightly smaller font size and consider using italics to distinguish it from the main text.</li>
</ul>
<ol start="4">
<li><strong> Saving the Report: </strong></li>
</ol>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Periodically save your seminar report to avoid losing any changes you&#8217;ve made. Use &#8220;Save&#8221; or &#8220;Save As&#8221; to create a backup with a different name.</li>
</ul>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Instructions for Using Photoshop</strong></span></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Locate and launch the Photoshop program on your computer. It may be found in the Applications (Mac) or Programs (Windows) folder.</li>
<li>Click on &#8220;File&#8221; in the top menu and select &#8220;Open.&#8221;</li>
<li>Browse and select the photo you want to edit and click &#8220;Open.&#8221;</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Basic Editing: </strong></p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li>Crop: Select the Crop Tool to remove unwanted parts of the image or to focus on specific elements.</li>
<li>Adjust Brightness and Contrast: Use the Image &gt; Adjustments menu to modify brightness and contrast levels.</li>
<li>Color Balance: Enhance colors using the Image &gt; Adjustments &gt; Color Balance option.</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>Resizing an Image: </strong></p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li>Click on &#8220;Image&#8221; in the top menu, and select &#8220;Image Size.&#8221;</li>
<li>Input the desired dimensions for width and height. Ensure &#8220;Constrain Proportions&#8221; is checked to maintain the aspect ratio.</li>
<li>Click &#8220;OK&#8221; to apply the changes.</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>Saving Your Edited Image: </strong></p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li>Click on &#8220;File&#8221; and select &#8220;Save As&#8221; to save your edited image with a new name.</li>
<li>Choose the file format (e.g., JPEG, PNG) and quality level.</li>
<li>Click &#8220;Save&#8221; to store the edited image on your computer.</li>
</ol>
<p>These instructions will help you load and use photos in your seminar report and effectively utilize the Photoshop program to enhance and edit images as needed.</p>
</div>
